{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "In many Latin American cities, poorly paid police officers often live cheek by jowl with criminals. When violence erupts, low-level officers are easy targets.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by Graham Denyer Willis, doctoral candidate in urban studies and planning, calls attention to fact that police officers are being killed at alarming rates in Sao Paulo, Brazil; contends that these killings result from poorly paid police officers who must live in neighborhoods populated with and controlled by members of organized criminal gangs, and are therefore easy targets when violence flares.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "5", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "WILLIS", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Graham", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "Denyer"}], "original": "By GRAHAM DENYER WILLIS", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/02/opinion/sunday/in-brazil-poverty-is-deadly-for-police-officers.html", "lead_paragraph": "In many Latin American cities, poorly paid police officers often live cheek by jowl with criminals. When violence erupts, low-level officers are easy targets.", "headline": {"seo": "In Brazil, Poverty Is Deadly for Police Officers", "main": "What\u2019s Killing Brazil\u2019s Police?", "print_headline": "What\u2019s Killing Brazil\u2019s Police?", "content_kicker": "Opinion", "kicker": "Opinion"}, "_id": "50be622900315214fbb7d34f", "word_count": "986", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2012/12/02/sunday-review/02BRAZIL-SUB2/02BRAZIL-SUB2-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2012/12/02/sunday-review/02BRAZIL-SUB2/02BRAZIL-SUB2-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2012/12/02/sunday-review/02BRAZIL-SUB2/02BRAZIL-SUB2-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2012/12/02/sunday-review/02BRAZIL-SUB2/02BRAZIL-SUB2-articleLarge